   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.906_1.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>3 Reinacherstrasse</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Zürich</addrLine>
               </address>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1926-01-19">January, 19<hi rend="superscript"><hi rend="underline"
                           >th</hi></hi>1926.</date>
               </dateline>

               <address rend="recipient">

                  <addrLine>Thomas Hardy, <choice><abbr>Esq <hi rend="superscript">re</hi></abbr>
                        <expan>Esquire</expan></choice></addrLine>
                  <addrLine><placeName ref="#pl:Dorchester">Dorchester</placeName>.</addrLine>
               </address>

               <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
            </opener>


            <p>Will you allow me to send you by this post two little essays which contain the
               principal matter of <pb n="2" facs="uoedh_hl_h.906_2.jpg"/> a lecture I gave last
               year to an English speaking club here in <placeName ref="#pl:Zürich"
                  >Zürich</placeName>.</p>

            <p>For many years I have been an ardent admirer &amp; lover of your wonderful work. The
               humour in some of your novels reminds me sometimes of our own poet <persName
                  ref="#ps:GottfriedKeller">Gottfried Keller</persName>, who also possesses that
               tender irony that <pb n="3" facs="uoedh_hl_h.906_3.jpg"/> gives some of your
               characters such a rich humanity.</p>

            <p>My oldest pupils – girls of eighteen &amp; nineteen – have also been reading some of
               your poems these last four years; also <ref target="#bib:Hardy1872_GreenwoodTree"
                  >Under the Greenwood Tree</ref> &amp; <ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1874_FarFromTheMaddingCrowd">Far from the Madding Crowd</ref>,
               &amp; have always got much human insight &amp; many lasting impressions of the power-
                  <pb n="4" facs="uoedh_hl_h.906_4.jpg"/> ful character-drawing &amp; artistic
               beauty of your books.</p>

            <p>I thank you from my heart for all the beauty &amp; grandeur of your books, by which
               you have made the world the richer &amp; your readers more understanding &amp; more
               humane.</p>

            <closer>
               <salute>Yours very sincerely</salute>
               <signed>Lina Baumann.</signed>
            </closer>


         </div>
